<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Press release for Vientiane Times</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">DIS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold"> 44</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Quality of Life Association</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.1 Quality of Life </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(QLA) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was the first Lao Civil </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ociety </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rganisation to provide assistance and support to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unexploded ordinance (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UXO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> survivors in Lao PDR as well as to people with disabilities. In its daily activities, QLA sees the barriers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that people with disabilities (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PWD</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, including survivors, are facing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and tries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> break them down to empower PWD and develop opportunities for them to participate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fully in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">society</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, to contribute </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to the development of their countries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">advocate for their rights . </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.2 From QLA experience this can only be achieved if PWD benefit from mainstream and disability specific services as reflected by the twin track approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.3 PWD, including survivors, are people with a lot of capabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and not acknowledging </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would be detrimental to any development efforts. They should thus, directly or via their representative associations, be given </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">opportunity to participate actively </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the definition of policies and programs, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their implementation and monitoring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.4 Development program</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and policies should reflect those considerations so </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to be inclusive of and accessible to PWD, including survivors, from the very moment they are drafted to the moment they are implemented and assessed. Only then</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> development efforts  reach the most vulnerable and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PWD  benefit from them on an equal basis to other</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> thus making sure no one is left behind.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2. Introduction of the work of Quality of Life Association</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.1 To answer the need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of unexploded ordnance  victims, and people with disabilities  the Quality of Life Association  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> set up in 2011 and became the first Lao Civil Society Organisation  providing assistance and support services to victims of unexploded ordnance , people with disabilities  and poor families in the Xieng Khouang Province in Lao PDR.  The QLA Operational Team and Board of Directors are made up of Lao nationals, some of whom are UXO survivors. The objective to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">set up the association in Xieng Khuang province because it is one of the most bomb affected areas in Laos. “Xieng Khuang, know for the Plain of Jars, is also the plain of scars.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:16.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 9pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.2 The presence of the buried bombs affects the quality of life of local people in many ways. Economic development is stalled. Children need to learn at an early age that they must be careful around their homes and villages. Agriculture is more difficult and often dangerous. Many people who have survived an accident need expensive medical care and follow-up treatment; families who have lost a loved one also need economic support and new livelihoods.             </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.3 The QLA supports UXO affected communities and PWD through training on animal raising, weaving and dyeing, and the production of hand-crafted souvenirs. Another important aspect is emergency and long term medical care, including rehabilitation, as well as psycho-social support.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The QLA has run training courses for UXO accident survivors, family members of UXO victims and PWD in nine villages of the province</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The Association</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  targeted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">these villages </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for assistance after it conducted a survey among local communities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“We select 15 people representing 15 families in a village to attend a course. We firstly give priority to a UXO affected family member and UXO survivors and persons with disability because they are our target groups. Our second priority is poor families. After attending a training course on livestock or poultry raising, each person is given 600,000-700,000 kip to use as capital to undertake this activity. Those who attend a training course on weaving, making handicrafts or tailoring can sell their products at the QLA village shop.” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The association provides all the materials needed for trainees to make the products and pays them for each item in accordance with their ability and the orders placed by the QLA. A training course on tailoring has taught women how to sew small fabric bags to contain laptops and mobile phones.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The association will continue to help UXO affected communities and PWD in all districts of the province because a large number of people need assistance and have no permanent job</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to provide them with a regular source of income.                                                                      </span></p><p style="line-height:16.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 9pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.4 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Lao Government ratified the UNCRPD on 2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> September, 2009.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> After the ratification, the National Committee for  Disabled People (NCDP) and the Lao Disabled People’s Association (LDPA) ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> collaborated with other related Ministries by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dentify</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">seven</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Government officials as disability rights officers in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">seven</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> targeted ministries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ministry of Labour and Social Welfare, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inistry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ducation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inistry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inistry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ealth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inistry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ublic Work and Transportation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inistry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nformation and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ulture</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inistry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">J</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ustice. They</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> then train</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> selected government Ministries to formulate and implement Ministerial action plans to support the inclusion and development of persons with disabilities in the Lao PDR. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Lao Disability Decree is issued in order to determine principles, rules and measures </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> taken for the protection of rights and interes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ts of persons with disabilities;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to formulate policies on treatment, health rehabilitation, vocational training, employment promotion and other policies aiming at promoting self-development and self-reliance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for persons with disabilities;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to eliminate all forms of discrimination against persons with disabilities, in order to create </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">conditions for persons with disabilities to participate fully and on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">equal basis in social activities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Lao Disability Decree is not yet finalized by the Lao Government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Nevertheless, as of today in Lao PDR, PWD including survivors, are facing barriers to access basic services such as health, education and employment on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">equal basis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their peers. This lack of access to basic services leads to reduced opportunities to contribute to the economic, social and cultural life of their families and communities. The result is that PWD may not participate fully </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> social and community development and face additional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">difficulties to elevate their social and economic situation. So, the QLA is encouraging PWD, including survivors, in Xieng Khouang Province to participate in family and community life and contribute to  local development. However, when basic services are developed that are not accessible for UXO survivors and persons with disabilities, the challenges are often too difficult to overcome.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3. Reason for submitting evidence:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.1 Given the fact that QLA is a pioneer in this field in Lao PDR, it was of outmost importance for us to share our views. Besides, Lao PDR being the most affected country in terms of cluster munitions contamination, this was also an opportunity for us to call</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> synergies to be made between victim assistance and the broader disability and development frameworks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to make sure that there exist specific policies for survivors, especially thanks to victim assistance provisions in the Oslo and the Ottawa treaties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> but also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to make sure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that PWD, and thus including survivors, can benefit from the efforts that are made for the development of a country or of a region. Indeed, achieving our goals in term of development is illusory if PWD, including survivors and other vulnerable persons are left behind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as  has been recalled recently at the highest level with the report of the High </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">anel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  of the UN Secretary General</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and  the discussions around the post 2015 agenda.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.2 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Lao PDR is a least developed country experiencing poverty. The country is ranked 133 out of 177 nations in the Global Development index. Approximately 23% of the population lives on less than $1USD per day. Persons with disabilities are particularly vulnerable to poverty  in society. The Lao National Growth and Poverty Eradication Scheme (2003) reported physical and mentally handicapped/blind groups represent the highest percentage (18.5%) of people  at-risk of poverty in Vientiane Municipality. Lack of awareness and understanding by government policy makers and officials lead</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to exclusion of persons with disability from development programs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ue to cluster munitions and other UXO </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at least 50</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">525 mi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ne/</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ERW</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> casualties, including 29,506 people killed and 21,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">019 injured since 1964</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Knowing those figures, it is obvious any initiative taken now</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">create </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a society which is inclusive of PWD and where a broad range of services are accessible to all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will benefit  future generations and will have long lasting effects for themselves but also for their communities since they are, on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">equal basis to others, actors of change.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.3 Besides, I am myself a person with disability and I have met the barriers I am trying, as the executive director of QLA, to break. I was lucky to find support and to be able to continue my education and then get a job as it is sadly not the case for all PWD, including survivors who remain the poorest amongst the poor because they often do not have access to such services and opportunities. For instance in my own province there is right now only one Rehabilitation centre in Xiengkhouang city which provide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> such services like rehabilitation, prosthetic and orthotic to survivors and PWD by the CMR and COPE. It is far from most villages where survivors and PWD live and therefore very difficult to access it. For instance my friendwas injured in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1970s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> when she was sixteen. And she finally received </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">her prosthesis on 4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> April 2010 with the support of Handicap International and COPE. I would wish </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">all survivors and PWD </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">quickly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">access quickly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">supports we need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> because it means we can survive as human being. I am also part of a survivor initiative called the Lao Ban Advocates and this experience, thanks to a close collaboration with the Lao Government, including with the NRA, has proved to be efficient. We have been working hand in hand with various stakeholders to raise the voice of survivors and their affected communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and to help the government in elaborating a framework for addressing their needs. Such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">example demonstrates that the motto “Nothing about us without us” is a meaningful one and that joint efforts lead to great results.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4. Quality of Life recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">So, to ensure that people with di</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sabilities including UXO survivors are included in development wok, here are a few recommendations that QLA would like to share:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.1 Policy and programme development sh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be inspired by lived experiences and therefore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> PWD, including UXO survivors, shall be given the possibility to  participate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> actively</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the discussions and contribute fully to the elaboration of those policies and programs. Indeed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UXO survivors and PWD are often left behind, so to ensure an inclusive development, UXO survivors and PWD we should be included in the first planning, discussing and decision making processes related to development framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Disabled Peoples Organizations (DPOs) should play a prominent role in the implementation of policies and programs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and need to be supported</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n order to be able to take the lead in implementing, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">monitoring and evaluati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> development policies and programs for PWD </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and UXO survivor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> A twin track approach should be reflected:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> On </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">one hand</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as to ensure that the approach taken, when developing systems, strategies and projects for the general public, is inclusive of PWD, including survivors, be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in areas like health care services, employment programs, education programs, etc. On the other  specific measures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ould </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> also be taken to support the development and the empowerment of PWD, including survivors. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> All </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">mainstream services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> sh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ould </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> also be designed as to be fully accessible to PWD.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Many PWD and survivors are unable to access public buildings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> health care services because th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">se are not accessible. Sometimes, they will not benefit from available services in their communities due to problems </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> transportation or the fact they did not get access to information related to such services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.5 Along with other factors such as gender and age, policy and program development should make sure that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> data are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">disaggregated by disability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to ensure PWD, including survivors, benefit from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">programs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on an equal basis with others. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will also help </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">measuring the impact of those efforts made to tackle poverty and improve people’s li</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ves</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.6 Any step taken also implies action to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">support and strengthen </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Disabled Peoples Organizations (DPOs)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> so they can advocate for the rights of PWD and thus collaborate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the elaboration of policies that affect them with all the relevant stakeholders.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">3 December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>